				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f_0 = (1/2\pi )\cdot {\mathrm{d}}\phi _{{\mathrm{CEO}}}/{\mathrm{d}}t$$\end{document}that result due to dispersion induced phase- and group-velocity differences.

Detection of f0. As explained previously, the fact that f0 is related to the phase of the optical carrier makes it extremely difficult to access directly. In 1999 a method was proposed to produce a heterodyne beat at f021,22 by nonlinear self-referencing between the extremes of the optical comb spectrum (see Fig. 1b). The simplest manifestation of this technique is obtained by frequency doubling light from a comb mode on the low end of the optical comb spectrum and interfering it with fundamental light at twice the frequency such that4f0=2⋅νN−ν2N=2⋅(Nfr+f0)−(2N⋅fr+f0).\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
